<Document>
<name>Da Lat to Mui Ne</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Da Lat to Mui Ne</h2><p><i>South-Central Vietnam · Da Lat to Mui Ne via the Truong Son descent</i></p><p><b>From cool pine-covered highlands at 1,500 m down to red sand dunes and South China Sea fishing villages.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>227 km (141 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>5–6 hrs without stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>December–April (dry); May–October sees afternoon rain in the highlands</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Steep mountain switchbacks on the descent; truck and bus traffic; afternoon rains make hairpins slick; livestock on rural sections</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>437</td></tr></table><hr><p>Da Lat sits at 1,500 m on the Lang Biang Plateau — French colonial planners chose it as a hill station in the 1890s because they could grow strawberries and roses there. The road south drops 1,500 m through the Truong Son range to the dry coastal plain in around 80 km. The contrast in climate, vegetation, and people is total: pine and pseudo-Alpine architecture at the top, dragon-fruit plantations and Cham minarets at the bottom. Mui Ne sits beside enormous red and white dunes (sand-sledding is the local entertainment) and a fishing harbor where round basket-boats (thung chai) bring in the morning catch. The fish-sauce industry of Phan Thiet next door is one of Vietnam's oldest — bottles in your kitchen may have come from this 30 km of coast.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Da Lat</b> — French colonial hill station at 1,500 m. Crazy House (Hằng Nga Guesthouse) is a tree-shaped surrealist hotel by the architect daughter of a former Vietnamese president. Cog-railway to Trai Mat village (5 km).</li><li><b>Prenn Pass</b> — Top of the descent off the plateau. View south over the Don Duong reservoir; pine forests give way to deciduous tropical species lower down.</li><li><b>Bao Loc</b> — Tea and silk country. Roadside dragon-fruit plantations from here southward — Vietnam is the world's largest producer.</li><li><b>Phan Thiet</b> — Fish-sauce capital. Centuries-old factories along the river. Cham towers at Po Sah Inu (8th century) remind you that this coast was Cham territory before Vietnamese expansion southward absorbed it in the 17th century.</li><li><b>Mui Ne fishing village</b> — Round basket-boats (thúng chai) bring in fish each morning. Sunrise on the harbor with hundreds of these strange wickerwork bowls is one of Vietnam's iconic sights.</li><li><b>Mui Ne red dunes</b> — Surreal red dunes against blue sea — sand sledding for kids, photographs for adults. Best at sunrise/sunset; midday the sand is too hot to walk on.</li><li><b>Bau Trang white dunes</b> — Larger and whiter than the red dunes; quad bikes for hire. Lotus pond at the base flowers May–August.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
